## Steps

### 1. Log into Splunk

**Credentials:**
```plaintext
Username: admin
Password: rangeforce
```

---

### 2. Open the "Search & Reporting" App

- Navigate to **Search & Reporting** from the left panel.
- This is where all search queries will be executed.

---

### 3. Interface Tour

Key components of the Splunk search interface:
- ğŸ” **Search bar** (center)
- ğŸ•’ **Time picker** (top-right)
- ğŸ“ **Fields** (left panel)
- ğŸ“ƒ **Event list** (center results)

<p align="center">
  <img src="assets/screenshots/splunk_search_bar.png" alt="Splunk Search Bar">
  <br>
  <em>Search bar and time picker highlighted</em>
</p>

---

### 4. Run a Basic Search

Search for all events with the word `failed`.

```spl
failed
```

Make sure Time Picker is set to **All time**.

<p align="center">
  <img src="assets/screenshots/search_failed_event.png" alt="Search Failed Events">
  <br>
  <em>Search results showing failed login events</em>
</p>

---

### 5. Analyze Search Results

Once you search for `failed`, observe the following:
- Event timeline (top bar)
- Highlighted fields: `host`, `source`, `sourcetype`
- Sample event breakdown

<p align="center">
  <img src="assets/screenshots/event_analysis.png" alt="Event Field Breakdown">
  <br>
  <em>Analyzing fields in Splunk results</em>
</p>

---

## Knowledge Check

**Q1:** What is the date of the most recent event?  
ğŸ“… **A:** 5/27/20

**Q2:** What is the username of the most recent failed login?  
ğŸ‘¤ **A:** ubuntu

**Q3:** What is the source of the most recent event?  
ğŸ“„ **A:** `/var/log/splunk/default/linux_s_30DAY.log`

---

### 6. Run a Multi-Term Search

Add another keyword to narrow down results:

```spl
failed root
```

---

### 7. Run a Quoted Phrase Search

Search for an exact phrase using quotes:

```spl
"failed password for root"
```

This will match only those events that include the **exact phrase**.

**Result:**  
ğŸ“Œ **7282** matching events

